A3: SPL Library Checkouts

Introduction

I am not a big reader so I wanted to familiarize myself with some things I would have possibly checked out form the library as a kid: The Harry Potter Series and audio books. Along with those two observations, as a business major I was interested in how large publishing companies have cornered the market, so I did research into what share of the market those companies hold.

Summary Information

I think the most interesting values I calculated for this project are regarding the checkout rate of Audio books over the last 10 years. In 2013 Audio books accounted for 5.4% of the amount of paper books checked out by library patrons. In 2023 that percentage has jumped up to 72.7%.

Harry Potter books have a less correlated pattern over the data set period. That change in number of checkouts could come down to a variety of factors but at the series peak in 2020 there were nearly 22500 checkouts of Harry Potter material compared with less than 7500 checkouts in 2005, a difference of about 15000 checkouts.

Lastly, I used a pie chart to display the amount of checkouts by the top 10 largest publishers in the library. Collectively those 10 publishers make up about 16% of the librarys checkouts.

The Dataset

This data set was collected collaboratively by the Seattle Public Library and the artist George Legrady who collected the data as a coincidence to use in one of his works where he wanted to display different trends in the types of material library patrons were checking out. When the SPL stitched their data together they published it for public use. The observations within the data include if the material is physical or digital, the type of checkout(), a more specific material type, checkout year, checkout month, title of the piece, International Standard Book Number (ISBN): a numeric commercial book identifier, the materials creator, subject, publisher, and year it was published. The data was collected by George Legrady and SPL. I do not think there are ethical issues with this data. Seattle has a history of trying to make government entities more ethical than other big cities, and a library is a branch of public resource government that has few possible ethical issues. The biggest limitation with this data was its size. 9 gigabytes is enormous and working with that has been a struggle for my computer.

First Trends Over Time Chart

This chart illustrates how the amount of checkouts for audiobooks has drastically increased over the data set time period. As you can see, in 2005 the number of audiobook checkouts is minuscule in comparison to the amount of book checkouts that year. However with the proliferation of technology through the years, and a younger generation being less interested in reading, audiobooks have become 72.7% as popular as books in 2023 adjusted for a 12 month year.

Second Trends Over Time Chart

The next chart I made illistrates how much Harry Potter series media has been checked out since 2005. As you can see the peak amount of checkouts occurs in 2020. This is probably a result of general pandemic boredom forcing people who dont normally read to pick up a book, and what else would they go to but the most popular book series of the 21st century. The lowest number of checkouts was observed in 2005. This could be a consequence of the series not being finished in combination with the movie series not being released yet.

Your Choice

Lastly, I analyzed the amount of checkouts by the top 10 largest publishers in the library. The amount of checkouts of by those 10 publishers combined makes up 16% of the libraries checkouts. Obviously to command such a large share of the checkouts those companies must have engaged in aggressive mergers and other capitalist practices to become giant firms that hold an pseudo-oligopoly.
